# Adding Historic Marker Deep-Read Articles

This rule documents the process for adding a companion "deep read" article that expands on a historic marker's inscription.

## File locations

- **Article markdown**: `articles_information/markers/<slug>.md` (filename should match the marker `slug` in `historic-markers-curated.json`, or the base slug before a numeric suffix like `-2`)
- **Deep-read links (auto)**: `web/lib/markerDeepReads.generated.ts` — regenerated on every `npm run prebuild` from curated markers + marker article files
- **Deep-read overrides**: `web/lib/markerDeepReads.ts` — shared type in `markerDeepReadsTypes.ts`; use for clusters (e.g. several markers → one article) that should not be overwritten by the generator
- **Batch tooling**: `web/scripts/normalize-marker-articles.mjs` (dedupe/rename), `web/scripts/add-marker-article-frontmatter.mjs` (prepend frontmatter to files missing `---`), `web/scripts/generate-marker-deep-reads.mjs` (writes the generated map), `web/scripts/lint-marker-articles.mjs` (prebuild: fail on orphan filenames)
- **After adding/removing companion files or changing CSV**: run `node web/scripts/parse-historic-markers.js` so `historic-markers-curated.json` includes every marker that has a matching `articles_information/markers/<slug>.md` (companion tier), plus fixed umbrella slugs for the 1910 cluster (`building-from-the-ashes`, `pluck-and-good-fortune`, `sliderock-lookout-tower`) that use `1910_fire` via `markerDeepReads.ts`.
- **Marker data**: `web/data/historic-markers.json`
- **History trails**: `web/data/history-trails.json`

## Step-by-step process

### 1. Create the article file

Place the markdown file in `articles_information/markers/`. The filename should match the marker slug in `historic-markers-curated.json` (e.g. `lewis-and-clark-in-salish-territory.md`). Use frontmatter `slug` when the public URL must differ (e.g. `slug: lewis-and-clark-in-salish-territory-123385`).

**Required frontmatter:**

```yaml
---
title: "Article Title"
slug: marker-slug-with-id
type: montana-facts
tags: [history, relevant-tags]
featured: false
excerpt: "One-sentence summary for search and social."
hero_image: /images/hero-image.jpg
hero_alt: "Descriptive alt text"
meta_description: "SEO description, 150-160 chars."
related_towns: [town-slug]
related_topics: []
date_published: YYYY-MM-DD
date_modified: YYYY-MM-DD
---
```

**Content guidelines:**
- Minimum 600 words (300 absolute minimum for indexing)
- At least 2 internal links (to towns, other articles, or guides)
- Include a "See also" section linking back to the marker and related towns

### 2. Verify the marker exists

```bash
grep '"id": "123385"' web/data/historic-markers.json
```

Confirm the marker slug matches what you'll use in `markerDeepReads.ts`.

### 3. Link article to marker page

If the marker is **curated** and the article file exists at `articles_information/markers/<marker-slug>.md` (or `<base-slug>.md` when the marker slug ends with `-2`, `-3`, etc.), **`prebuild` adds the deep-read link automatically** via `generate-marker-deep-reads.mjs`.

For **several markers → one article** (e.g. the 1910 fire cluster), add or adjust entries in `web/lib/markerDeepReads.ts` under `MARKER_DEEP_READS_FIRE` (those override the auto map). Use marker slugs **without** legacy `-12345` URL suffixes—they must match `m.slug` from `historic-markers-curated.json`.

### 4. Check if marker is in a history trail

```bash
grep '"123385"' web/data/history-trails.json
```

If found, the marker page will show the trail badge automatically.

### 5. Build and verify

```bash
cd web && npm run build
```

**Verify these items:**
- Article page exists: `ls out/information/<slug>/`
- In search index: `grep '<slug>' public/search-index.json`
- In sitemap: `grep '<slug>' out/sitemap-information.xml`
- Deep-read link on marker: check `out/historic-markers/<slug>/index.html` for "Further reading" section

### 6. Commit and push

```bash
git add articles_information/markers/<file>.md web/lib/markerDeepReads.ts web/lib/markerDeepReads.generated.ts web/public/search-index.json
git commit -m "Add <title> deep-read article

Marker companion article at /information/<slug>/
linked from the historic marker page (auto-generated map or override in markerDeepReads.ts)."
git push
```

## Checklist summary

- [ ] Article in `articles_information/markers/`
- [ ] Frontmatter complete (title, slug, meta_description, related_towns, dates)
- [ ] Content ≥600 words with ≥2 internal links
- [ ] "See also" section links to marker + related towns
- [ ] Curated marker slug matches article filename (or override / cluster entry in `web/lib/markerDeepReads.ts`); `markerDeepReads.generated.ts` updated by `prebuild`
- [ ] Build succeeds (`npm run build`)
- [ ] Article in sitemap and search index
- [ ] Deep-read link visible on marker page
- [ ] Committed and pushed

## Scaling notes

Curated markers with a matching `articles_information/markers/<slug>.md` file are linked automatically. Remaining gaps (marker slug ≠ filename, non-curated markers) still need manual overrides in `markerDeepReads.ts` or filename/slug alignment.
